my dryer vent goes out of the roof (dumb). when my clothes would stop drying properly, i'd have to get my husband to go up there and clean the vent. rain, dew and humidity would cause the lent to clump up and not be capable of blowing out. we have a really steep pitch and my husband was sick of going up there. he ordered the system these filters go in and installed it in the garage. my dryer still wasn't drying properly. actually, it wasn't drying at all, really. he played with the system for a bit, finally pulling the filter out and told me to try it like that. my clothes are now drying faster than ever. the system itself has a screen in it. we just rub the lent off of the screen and call it a day. if you get the system, don't waste your time or money on the filters.

apartment living can mean dreaded trips to the laundromat but no more with this wonderful washer. given our lease, we wanted to be able to hide the washer and this will fit through any closet door 24" wide or more. the side drain hose means you'll need at least 25" width or 25" deep by rotating sideways. assembly wasn't bad, just take your time and read the instructions. the hardest part was attaching the caster wheels. delivery was a 4hr window 10-2 and that's when it arrived. the guys carried it up 2 flights and i tipped them. this washer is amazingly quiet which is important and it holds more than i thought. it will fit a queen-size set of sheets plus 2 bath towels. it holds lots of underwear or shirts. the comforter and rugs will still need the laundromat. there are a ridiculous number of settings. the permanent press setting really did leave fewer wrinkles on dress shirts. the washer shuts off if you open the top door. be sure to empty the lint screens often. great price! tips: instead of trying to attach the end of the drain hose to the faucet attachment, just use the curved clamp to hook around the faucet base. definitely put the wheel locks on when it's running or it will try to roll away potentially damaging the faucet and attachment. as a portable, you get an extra faucet hose if ever needed. when washing with warm water, wait until it's filled and then turn off the warm water and turn on the cold water for rinsing. when it's done i just stick both hoses inside the washer which leaves the door slightly open to dry out. the manufacturer said this model is discontinued so you shouldn't wait while they're still in stock. complaints: too much styrofoam packing material! there shouldn't be any since styrofoam does not recycle. separate it from the recyclable cardboard forms and bag the nasty stuff for the landfill.

this is a great little washing machine that serves its purpose. i‚Äôll start with the pros. pros: -fits in small spaces (16 inches wide) -fully automatic -not to loud -easy to use -pretty cute -led interior light -really good cleaning -doesn‚Äôt use much water -doesn‚Äôt need that much soap -really dries clothes to about 95%. clothes dry fast after being hung -changed our lives to have in until laundry cons: -the width is indeed 16 inches but you have to factor in the tubing on the side which is another inch and half. that puts you at 17. 5 inches wide. i had to drill a hole in the back on my machine to require the pump so it would fit in the space i had. -there is no timer on the machine so you have no idea how long your load has been in for -the high water level setting will leak. it‚Äôs simply took much water for the washing machine with clothes in it and it will overflow. stick to medium and low water level settings. -ultimately both the pump and the hose are comically short. you‚Äôll need to buy replacements for both. that will set you back another $20. i would recommend at least a 5 foot hose and then a 6 foot pump. get someone who knows a bit about pluming to make sure the hose is secured on tight when you replace it. -can‚Äôt really use it out of the box. have to get all the extra parts and do some minor fixing. -you will also want to buy a quick release converter for your sink to make your life easier. that will set you back another $10. -the instructions make absolutely no sense. they are google translated from another language. -this model is more expensive than the giantex model that holds only 8 lbs of laundry and has a timer. if i had more space, i would have gone in that direction instead. also it‚Äôs $176 instead of the $250 this machine cost you.

i‚Äôm a chef, so the gold standard of cooking is gas. however, where i live gas is an extra expense that has to be stored on your own property in a tank. after much research, this was my next best option. i‚Äôm pleasantly surprised how much control i have with induction. changing the setting even one degree is immediate. the heat distribution is better than gas, because it encompasses the entire pan; not just the center. great stove top. the right bottom burner is the most commonly used, so i wish there was one more that size. the temptation to wiggle the pan on the stovetop is an adjustment that takes a minute. my old habit yielded a scratch in the first week. lesson learned. thankfully all my cast iron cookware works brilliantly on induction. if it‚Äôs not enameled, i recommend placing a paper towel under the pan while cooking. slight scratches are now forming as with all glass cooktops, but it‚Äôs much easier to clean than a conventional glass cooktop because the burner itself doesn‚Äôt heat up; only the pan. just maybe there‚Äôs a new gold standard in stovetops.

this is the dishwasher for you if you like having to remove water from it with a wet vacuum or leaks! really wanted to like this portable dishwasher but it is a huge fail on too many levels. the literature it comes with needs a lot of work. they tell you in the online ad that you can hook it up permanently like a full-size dw but nothing about that is mentioned in the literature. it is possible though, you just need to find the right adapter at your local big box store. now, the lines it comes with have plastic connectors to the back of the dishwasher, very chintzy. cheap. and if you try to use any kind of pliers to tighten them, just don't because you run the risk of cracking them. we did plumb ours in like a regular dw, it was connected to the garbage disposal dw connection, and plugged into the gfci outlet under the sink cabinet. the dw comes with a normal, heavily soiled, and lightly soiled cycle (20-minute one), with high hopes ran a "test" cycle, the 20-minute one. this thing is about as noisy as most dishwashers when it starts to run. 12 minutes into the cycle it started to discharge the water (or so we thought). we waited for the end-of-cycle indication and opened the door only to find it was filled with water at the bottom of it, not a little bit of water, but a whole lot. had to use a wet vacuum to remove the water. for the first cycle, we had it connected to an extension discharge hose (a normal size one because the hoses that it comes with for the discharge are not normal size). check the manual reasons it might not discharge. according to the manual, possible causes are: 1) kinked discharged hose. checked the hose. no kinks. 2) stopped up sink drain. check drain. totally clear. 3) dw filter clogged. no dishes are in the dw so there was nothing to clog any filter. after removing the water with a wet vac, we decided to run another test cycle. in the second cycle, we removed the extension discharge hose and connected the dw directly to the garbage disposal dw connection just using the discharge hose the dw came with and a dw rubber adapter (the kind one would normally use). ran the 20-minute cycle again, and 12 minutes into the cycle it started to throw an e4 error. look at the error codes in the manual, and find out it means "overflow". seriously? according to the manual, possible causes: "some element of the dishwasher leaks". smh. at this point, we cut power to the dw, open the door and the bottom is full of water again. used the wet vac to remove the water, and pulled the dw forward while keeping it level and it is leaking from the bottom. the manual tells you to "call for service" if an overflow occurs. really? have not even been able to use it once normally and one needs to call for repair service? it is a piece of junk. at this point, we are over this fiasco. not worth it! i did go back and re-read other reviews and this appears to be a common issue that other customers have reported experiencing with it even when just connected directly to a faucet. it has been processed for a return! save your sanity, time, and $$$. pass on this one!

i read a number of fairly negative reviews of this product. they caused me concern, but i am very happy to say that this product does exactly what i want without any fuss or bother. i've had my vue for over a year. in fact, i have two. keurig (green mountain coffee roasters) discontinued the vue some time ago and have slowly reduced the variety of beverages available for the vue. that's really too bad since the additional capacity of vue cups permits brewing full strength coffee in 12, 14, or 16 oz quantities. one product i particularly loved was the sweet ice tea. it was an incredibly convenient way to make a single glass of iced tea in under a minute. all you do is take a 20oz glass, fill it with ice, insert the ice tea vue cup in the brewer, selected iced drinks/tea and start. it produced a perfect glass every time. one of the first casualties when keurig discontinued the vue brewer was the sweet and unsweet iced teas. i was not a happy camper. then i read about this product. i ordered a box of kcup lipton sweet iced tea and when the k2v arrived, i just took a kcup, placed it in the k2v, pressed down so the needle in the adapter could puncture the kcup, and then brewed the iced tea exactly the way i would with the vue cup. the results were perfect! brewing kcup coffee is also possible. please bear in mind that the reduced amount of grounds in a kcup will not brew full strength coffee in you brew more than 10 ounces. other than that, results are perfect. i didn't try the gold filter cup that comes with the k2v (it lets you use your own grounds). frankly, that makes no sense to me. there are a lot easier ways to brew a single cup of coffee with your own grounds than trying to force a vue brewer to do it. go to a starbucks and watch them brew "poured" coffee. so, if you want the ability to take advantage of kcup variety and still hang on to your keurig vue brewer, this device is a perfect way to do it.

i had a haier washer in the past which i gave away when i briefly moved to an apartment with a washer/dryer. then i moved again to an apartment without and knew i had to buy another one. i went with this one because it seemed to have more capacity than the haier, which also happened to not be available anymore. i like this a lot more. the haier seemed very unstable due to the wheels and build overall and often the spin cycle went off balance and the drum would start banging/shaking. this one is very stable and the spin cycle is unbelievably quiet. it also seems to remove more water on the spin cycle than any washer i've used in the past, making it much easier to dry your clothes. i bought the costway mini dryer with it and that seems to work well too. i also like that this has many different programs to choose from. you have the option to select two rinse cycles or just one. currently, filling the washer has been kind of tricky for me since the inlet hose doesn't fit any of my faucets, but i am working on a more permanent solution for that. in the meantime, it is possible to manually fill (albeit more cumbersome). i have found that a water siphon (the kind you use for aquarium water changes) works well with one end placed below your faucet and the other end into the washing basin to avoid having to fill and pour with a bucket. bear in mind, this is for smaller than standard loads of laundry, but i found i can fit way more in this one than a 1 cubic foot capacity portable washer. if you have a small family and like the convenience of having your own washer, this is it. using communal laundry machines seem very unappealing to me, especially during covid, so this is a great solution.

filters are one of those products that you have to accept manufacturer published specs for. there's no practical way to test these without the resources of a lab. it's all about trust. ge is a major player, has a ~130 year history and like many large and established us companies is highly process driven, innovative and fully embraces quality control and data driven results. the published specs for their mwf filter are below. one huge caveat: the ge appliances sub-brand is now owned or controlled by chinese company haier and kkr, a global investment firm. unknown how much of the typically high performing and capable ge culture and run rules will remain intact over the long run. i have no reason to believe that the amazon premium mwf filter is more or less effective than ge's but cost no object, i'd go with the ge filter simply because of trust. i like that the ge pharmaceutical filtration is third party tested. if i lived in an area where water management is suspect or in a heavily populated area with who knows what being flushed or otherwise sent down the drain to a water management plant, i'd go with the ge. the level of filtration you need goes hand in hand with how well your local municipality does with water management. the city i live in is diligent about water quality and publishes an annual and detailed report of the testing. they test for thousands of contaminants. in other words, the water in my area is most likely safe for consumption. not true in all areas. if your water is managed by a transparent and professional municipality, is well funded and staffed, going with a 'lesser' filter than the ge is probably ok. filter performance in my case is more about filtering out hard water taste. so, should you buy the amazon filter? i'd say yes if you trust those that manage your water quality. the amazon premium filter seems to filter out taste as well as the ge. both this and the ge are rated for 6 months/300 gallons usage. lt fits well and doesn't leak. cautiously recommended. the amazon filter specs are above in the advertising. ge specs below. ge mwf specs: filter life 6 months max. filtered water flow (gpm) 0. 5 filter media carbon block operation water pressure (psi) 40 min. - 120 max. nsf/ansi 42 yes nsf/ansi 53 yes pharmaceutical filtration - claims tested/verified by independent laboratory, not certified by nsf international or state of ca yes state of ca certified yes asbestos reduction >99% atrazine (herbicide) reduction 94. 5% benzene reduction 96. 7% chlorine taste and odor reduction 97. 5% cysts reduction 99. 99% lead reduction 99. 3% @ 6. 5 ph and 99. 3% @ 8. 5 ph lindane reduction (a pesticide) 99% mercury reduction 93. 2% @ 6. 5 ph and 93. 2% @ 8. 5 ph nominal particulant class 1 99. 7% p-dichlorobenzene reduction 99. 8% tetrachloroethylene 96. 7% toxaphene reduction 93. 2% atenolol 99. 5% endrin 97. 1% fluoxetine 99. 4% ibuprofen 94. 1% progesterone 99. 5% trimethoprim 99. 5%

i bought this dishwasher because i am almost never home, doing it by hand uses a lot of water. did i mention that i'm lazy when i get home? build quality from the outside is okay it looks nice but the sheet metal is thinner than what you find on a refrigerator or stove. so in other words kind of delicate. the led display that shows the time remaining is visible when the door is opened, but when you close it you have to look between the door and the frame to see it which is kind of annoying. the inside frame is good, spacious for its size. from top to bottom is the same size as a built-in dishwasher, from side to side is about 4 to 6 inches shorter then a built-in dishwasher. the top and bottom metal racks have a durable coating on them. my only concern about the inside is that the top rack has a spray arm that completely detaches from the base in the back when you pull it out (which is normal). i wonder how long it will last before i have to replace the seal. if you follow the instructions that is given, it is pretty much straight forward and easy to install. the one thing that really surprised me. the sink attachment that they put in with it. it has threads on the outside and threads on the inside. it makes it a more versatile install pending on your sink faucet. overall i was impressed. the outer build quality was decent. the inner build quality was good. i got this a week ago. i have used it 4 times and the functionality was excellent. as for the price it's a little much but if i had went to a competitive store it would have cost me a $150 more.

i'm very pleased with this product and i'm sure you will be as well providing you don't confuse it with a full-size unit. the main reason i'm writing this is to mention, unlike the company's customer service department claimed, it will work without being directly connected to a water source. admittedly, it's easier if connected to a water line but not that much trouble to fill manually. here's how i do it: fill the tub up with water, add detergent, stir the water to mix, add clothes. next turn on power, select water height to high, press "cycle button" three (3) times for "wash only, " then press start. the wash cycle takes about 15 minutes to complete. once wash cycle is completed press power button turning off machine. next, push power button again to turn on. press cycle button five (5) times for "rinse only. " then press start, which drains the water out of the tub. after completed turn off machine and repeat the above "wash only" steps (listed above) but just fill with water. let clothes agitate in rinse water for about 5 minutes and push the power button turning the machine off. repeat "rinse only steps" (above). i rinse clothes two or three times this way. when finished push power button off. after rinsing is complete push power on, press "cycle button" six (6) times for rinse only, then press start. there you have it. i use a separate spinning unit to drying the clothes as much as possible before hanging them to air-dry. when drying this i use multiple plastic hangers (at least three) so as not to put marks in the clothes. thanks for reading my review and happy washing!

we use these motors to keep the bath and kitchen fans functioning in a 1962 apartment building. here are a few easy ways to make them work. but first, make sure you need a new one. take your motor out and spin the blade or cage by hand. also push and pull it in the direction of the shaft and see if it moves in and out of the motor enough to rub the housing or frame. most of the time, our noise complains are a function of the blade or cage coming loose and contacting some stationary metal part; or just needing shifted on the shaft to compensate for shaft loosening over time. if it all seems good, then remove the blade/cage and put a few drops of machine oil in the oil well (if so equipped) or drip in at the base of the shaft. now plug the motor in. if it doesn't spin easily, then you'll need a new one. our original kitchen vents run a clockwise motor. when we switch them over, we simply flip the fan blade and re-install. you can change the direction of the motor by disassembling and flipping the middle section, but this is definitely motors 201, so do so to your own comfort and at your own risk. flipping the blade is easier if possible. on our bath fans, we have a squirrel cage which is not reversible, but fortunately, the originals are ccw. however, these mount with studs on the shaft side, not the back side. so we simply remove the through-bolt (one at a time) and reverse them. the shaft length is not constrained in either of our fans, but if you have interference, just shorten the shaft with a cut-off wheel, hacksaw or whatever works for you. pull chain switches and bead chain are available on amazon. choose the switches that are at least partially metal. since this motor is the only style easily had, it's good to know how to creatively make them work in your application. i hope this is helpful to you.

here is what i found out. if you hear the clicking sound coming from your icemaker samsung imc 701 or ge da97-05422a, it has no serviceable electric parts so replace the icemaker. most likely the heater on the tray has failed. the clicking is the motor trying to turn the paddles against a mass of ice that has not been pre-empted from the tray for paddles to discharge the ice cubes. do not replace the motherboard if replacing the ice maker with clicking occurs. if the icemaker does cycle (paddles move to 3 oclock position facing it) with a clean ice tray then you may have a motor failure or something further up the line (in the motherboard). i went round and round on this and spoke with ge customer service. the bulletin by samsung everyone talks about on the internet is misleading. start with the icemaker, it is the cheapest solution and can be purchased amazon verified as of 3/15 for under $100. our ice maker lasted 7 years which is close to when all icemaker fail. it is a tough environment for motors and electronics in general. hope this helps someone. cheers!

hello. i cannot review this part accurately because i do not know if it works. i just want to pass along some advice. my ge quietpower3 inlet valve died and the dishwasher would not stop filling and flooded the kitchen. no big deal, i ordered an aftermarket part from ebay for $17. when i opened it up it came with different size orifi (sp? ) and two of the parts on the back where the power connects, one black and one blue. my dishwasher takes the black one. anyway, i was supposed to re-use the metal bracket from my original valve. turns out the screw pattern on that one, and this part are bigger than the one on my dishwasher (website for that and this part said i had correct part) so i tried to make it work and it lasted about two days and another flood. my fault. anyway, i ordered this part because it is original ge and i didn't want another flood. showed up quickly, looked good, but had the larger screw pattern. installed it and it did not work. that is when i realized it had the blue electrical part. pulled it, swapped the first replacement part onto this parts metal frame and we are now back in business. so, word of warning, make sure the size of the screw pattern you need and the color of the part with the electrical leads.

we put this in with our new kitchen cabinets and appliances. all in all, it's quite a deal. the fan is powerful and effective, and smooth running. the stainless steel is solid, as is the general construction. the lights, as everyone has commented, are a joke. just for decoration really. don't know how easy it would be to replace them as they are leds and in a sealed container. the contractor had to get the upper sleeve trimmed down at a metal shop in order to fit our low (91-inch) cape-style ceilings. i wanted the lowest part of the hood to be at least 69 inches off the ground to avoid collisions with my forehead. so some trimming was necessary. it contains a much more powerful fan (turbo-style) for far less money than the ones sold by the big-name appliance makers. and with a little ingenuity i think this hood can be adapted to almost any situation. the fan has a very smooth sound, and electronic controls are nice too. there are 3 clearly marked speeds. if you hit the off button, it gives you a 1-minute delay before turning off. if you want it off right away, hit the speed-button that you used to turn it on, or hit the off-button twice. very simple and intuitive. the stainless steel is solid, but the usual pain in the a to keep clean. (glad we got the new smudge-proof stainless finish on our frigidaire appliances. it shows a lot less fingerprints. ) i would have preferred a slightly less space-age style, but i didn't see anything more appropriate. we got cherry cabinets in a deep red/brown wood finish and stainless appliances for a kind of mixed traditional/modern style. maybe the similar akdy model with the flat glass would have worked better. . . should'a, could'a, would'a. that's my refrain for the first 6 to 8 months on all home improvement projects. after a year i get used to it, and wonder why i ever wanted anything different. same with new clothes.

was easy to use and worked perfect! no more brownish-rusty dishwasher interior. looks brand new again! i used a dremel rotary tool, sanded off every speck of rust! sand any "lumps" (which are hidden "rust dust") to make sure no rust left behind! i sanded down to bare metal, cleaned every spot i sanded with rubbing alcohol on a cotton pad, twice. don't skimp on the prep! people who said it "didn't work" did not prep correctly! did 3 coats, almost the whole bottle. do it outside to see clearly and wear latex gloves. i let each coat dry 1 hour, then let finished rack dry 48 hours, before i did a load of dishes. i opened my dishwasher and all the brown was gone! yes the goop dries fast. keep a finger over the bottle. by the 3rd coat, it was getting so thick, i thinned with 1/2 teaspoon 100% acetone nail polish remover, capped and shook it good. exposure to air dries the goop quick! the trick is>>> don't "brush" the goop on ‚Äî use the brush to quickly spread the goop along the wires. using a light touch ‚Äî then back off and close the bottle! if you use extra brush strokes, it gets stiff and lumpy. keep bottle closed ‚Äî every time you open the bottle to air, it gets thicker (and harder to spread). don't expect a factory coating ‚Äî but it will be sealed. you hardly see the repairs! do the prep right. get every speck of rust off first, then wipe it down good with alcohol. read the instructions!

if i could give this 6 out of 5 stars, i would. 11/10. 100% satisfied. i live in a small apartment and my job has me working long hours. when i get home from work or on my rare day off i have a really hard time bringing myself to go do laundry at a laundromat. not that i mind doing laundry, but the sorting it, packing it up, hauling it all to a laundromat along with laundry detergent, paying $5+ every time just to spend about 1. 5 to 2 hours sitting and waiting for the laundry to finish all while it being around 10 or 11 at night? yeah, i put it off as long as i can every single time. like, until the only thing left to wear are the ugly christmas sweater and the shorts i've had since middle school level of put it off. after a while i started washing things by hand in the bathtub because i hated the laundromat process so much, but that was such a tedious process involving a plastic magazine file bin, kitchen tongs, and scalded hands. needless to say, it was a dark time where laundry was concerned. i was hesitant to purchase this at first due to price, but y'all, i wish i had purchased this sooner. it's so easy. it takes two minutes to wash things (but i double that because two minutes of washing feels weird), so i pop on a good song and spin it until it's done. the entire process can be done in the bathtub: the spinning, the draining, the rinsing, and then scoot it over and your drying rack can fit in there too. it takes a while to drain if the lid stays on (the instructions recommend keeping it on for hot water until it cools), but since i'm at home, i can just go do other things. if the water is tepid just pop that lid off and it drains quick. i'm not stuck staring at a spinning washer hoping someone doesn't steal my clothes. then a quick rinse, let it drain, dry your clothes, and go back to your day. it's hands-on work for only roughly 10 minutes. it's awesome. it fits a lot more clothes than i anticipated, too. i use those 13" x 13" cube bins as a laundry hampers for each type of clothes so they're already sorted, and the washer can fit pretty much an entire bin's worth of clothes. i was shocked at how much i could wash at once. even though it's expensive, a quick calculation showed it would pay for itself in 16 trips to the laundromat (and a trip to the laundromat runs roughly 2 loads of what this can handle), so that's basically 32 washes. but forget the money part. not having to deal with the entire process of going out to do laundry, and not having that chore hanging over my head basically at all times. that alone is worth it. i already have to spend all day every day outside of my apartment and i just don't want to leave my place on my days off. and with winter coming, laundry days lugging dirty clothes through nasty nyc street slush is *miserable*, but now i don't have to! plus, it's kind of fun! i'm actually looking forward to doing my laundry now. it's worth it to me to finally have a full closet of clean clothes and not losing things to endless pit of the "dirty" hamper! i am 100% a fan of this. if you have ever found yourself washing clothes by hand at any point, just do yourself a favor: buy this washer and thank me later.

i received my bellemain frothing pitcher (12 oz) this evening and could not wait to try it. i was very pleased with the simplicity of the design and apparent quality of the pitcher, and was even happier when i made my first butterfly pea flower latte! i use plant and nut milks, my favorite for lattes being oat milk. within seconds, the pitcher was filled with perfectly frothed oat milk; i prefer thick froth, and this pitcher did not disappoint! pouring was smooth and precise with no drips at all. i waivered between a 12 oz and 20 oz, but decided the 12 oz should be fine, and it was. because the volume of liquid increases as air is whipped into it, it makes plenty for one to two mugs, depending on mug size and how you make your beverage. i heat about 1/4 c of water to steep the butterfly pea flowers in, then fill a mug about 1/3 full with oat milk and heat. i add the butterfly pea flower tea to the heated milk and then poured in the frothed milk (i filled the frothing pitcher about 1/3 of the way with cold, full fat oat milk (fav brand is oatly) and added a little califia almond/coconut milk vanilla creamer. it frothed up beautifully in no time at all). my mug was filled to the brim - hands down the best latte i have had - what a difference frothing the milk makes! the pitcher was easy to clean and is so pretty in its simplicity and craftsmanship that i am leaving it out on display - plus i‚Äôll be using it everyday anyway. it can also be used to serve creamers as it looks lovely on the table.

i cross threaded the plastic part while putting back up the hose on my kenmore he4t. unfortunately it wasn't fixable. so i ordered this part form amazon and the only difference is the color of the water hose attachment (grey versus blue, who cares? ). it fitted perfectly and the screw hole matched with no problems. the part had on the box certified whirlpool so i'm assuming it is oem. after the repair i did a laundry and checked for leaks, everything was good so i guess it will be just fine. my washer is 10 years old but still working properly so it was worth it to change this part for cheap and install it myself. you have good reviews in here on how to do it with pictures and step so if you are in trouble, that would help you. i put a dab of silicone grease on the threads in order to help for sealing but also to ease the process of screwing in the hose as metal on plastic may be a bit rough. next time i'll know better but this is how you learn. thanks to amazon for providing next day shipping.
